  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Legal formatting is the process by which a cultural practice, social relation, or community dynamic is translated into a legal category that the state\u0026rsquo;s apparatus can process. The term generalizes from the specific case of evidentiary credentialing to name the broader dynamic: the legal system doesn\u0026rsquo;t observe social realities as they are; it reformats them into administrable units.\nFormatting operates through the combined mechanisms of adversarial procedure (which requires everything to serve an argumentative purpose), evidence rules (which determine what the court can receive), and legal personhood (which determines whose perspective enters the record). The result is a one-way translation: social realities enter the legal system and emerge as legal artifacts. The reverse — legal artifacts returning to their social form — doesn\u0026rsquo;t occur.\n",
